<td background="/lotr/gfx/mom/blu_05.gif" class="headerbg"><font class="h1font"><font color="#FFFFFF"><table cellspacing=0 cellpadding=0 border=0 width=100%><TR><td><font class="h1font">Tournament Reports</td><form method='post' action=''><td align='right' valign='bottom'><select name='select' onChange='go(this)'><option selected>More DeckTech Tournament Reports</option><option value='#'> </option><option value='/starwarsccg/treports/index.php3'>Star Wars: CCG</option><option value='/heroclix/treports/treports.php'>HeroClix</option><option value='/vs/treports/treports.php'>Marvel VS</option><option value='/lotr/treports/treports.php'>Lord of the Rings</option><option value='/magic/treports/treports.php'>Video Games and Movies</option><option value='/wars/treports/treports.php'>Wizards Minis</option></select></td></form></tr></table></font></B></td><td background="/lotr/gfx/mom/blu_06.gif"></td></tr>
	<tr><td background="/lotr/gfx/mom/whi_07.gif"></td>
		<td bgcolor="#FFFFFF" background="/lotr/gfx/mom/whi_08.gif"><font class="bfont"><font class="h1font"> Joliette, Quebec, Canada    February 1st<br></font><br><font class="h2font"> <b>Overall Rating:</b> </font><img src="/lotr/gfx/star2.gif" width="19" height="21" border="0" align="absmiddle"><img src="/lotr/gfx/star2.gif" width="19" height="21" border="0" align="absmiddle"><img src="/lotr/gfx/star2.gif" width="19" height="21" border="0" align="absmiddle"><img src="/lotr/gfx/star2.gif" width="19" height="21" border="0" align="absmiddle"><img src="/lotr/gfx/star2.gif" width="19" height="21" border="0" align="absmiddle"><font size='1'>(4.87)</font><br><font class="h2font"> <b>Author:</b> <A HREF='http://www.decktech.net/lotr/main/mpage.php?member=11045'>Patrick "Patrick M. S" Sullivan</A></font><font class="afont"> <a href='http://www.decktech.net/lotr/main/mpage.php?member=11045&sub=1'> (Subscribe to this member)</a><br><font class="h2font"> <b>Date Submitted:</b> February 3, 2003</font><p align='justify'><blockquote><font class="bfont"> Joliette, Quebec, Canada (Saturday, February the 1st, 2003)<br />
<br />
Pre-Tourney thoughts<br />
<br />
So here I am gearing up for another run to Joliette for an Open Block tourney. I was there two weeks prior and pulled off an undefeated win. However, I made a major ruling error regarding the archery phase. One of the up and coming players was playing Uruk archery and had exhausted his minions using Cloud of Arrows (he also discarded his Weapons of Isengard). I then proceeded to shoot the minions with my directed archery, thinking I would reduce his archery to zero because there were no minions left. He said I was incorrect and I convinced him that I was right and now in the end in turns out I was wrong. Many discussions have taken place in the review section of Decktech and especially in the forum of GPN. I have to give a big thanks to Josh from Toronto, Jean-Luc Simard from Montreal, Alan Sagan from BC and William Dinega from the States for helping me get the official rulings from Decipher and helping me see my blunder. Someone else pointed out that I should be ashamed for being a 1926-rated player and not mastering the rules. I would argue that mastering the rules and mastering the game are two very different things. In SW: CCG, I had a true mastery of the rules (often correcting World Champion Raphael Asselin on ruling mistakes he was making) but I was one of the WORST players in the world. My point is, even in LOTR, some of the best players in the world still don&#8217;t quite understand things like site control (and place tokens on the sites to show where they have taken control even though your fellowship is still there (nice move, BadBeef &#61514;). We are all learning the rules as we go. I think my misunderstanding of the archery was because of Orc Bowmen where I used to eliminate the Orcs so I wouldn&#8217;t have to deal with the +4 archery minion total. <br />
<br />
So now for today&#8217;s tournament, I face a bit of a dilemma regarding J. Bolduc (my opponent from two weeks ago).  Do I wait until the next time this ruling comes up and then point out that I made a mistake? Or do I bit the bullet and approach J. Bolduc as soon as I see him, telling him I made a terrible mistake and that his deck was better than he thought. I think I&#8217;ll go for the latter since it commands more courage. I&#8217;m lucky in that even if we had played it correctly two weeks ago, I still would have won the game. It ended up not being a material issue in the way both our decks came out. <br />
<br />
The day of the tourney:<br />
<br />
Anyway enough nostalgia, I need to focus on today. I will be playing the same deck I played two weeks ago for two reasons. One, I really need to know if it&#8217;s any good and one tourney win isn&#8217;t enough to know. Secondly, I like giving the locals a real chance at beating me. They often tech their decks against what they think I&#8217;ll be playing and I&#8217;d hate to disappoint them. So let&#8217;s see if they&#8217;ve anticipated me bringing back my Moria or if they think I&#8217;ll go back to my trusty Uruks. <br />
<br />
The deck I&#8217;m playing is a fellowship based around men (Aragorn, Boromir, Eowyn and believe it or not, Theoden) with an interesting Moria variant. Instead of going for the usual site 7 kill, I&#8217;m going for a more flexible shadow including 3 Cave Trolls, 3 Wallcrawlers and no underground sites! It should catch many people off-guard. Also it cycles real well to aid my fellowship in setting up (which is fairly possession-reliant, although there are some skirmish events thrown in for good measure, another reason not to play Cavern Entrance). Almost all Moria decks are built towards a shadow win. Mine is built around a fellowship win. Cave Troll has stopping power and Moria cycles for my fellowship. I hope all goes according to plan. <br />
<br />
So as usual I drove to the tournament (which is almost an hour&#8217;s drive north-east of Montreal) alone in my green Honda Civic (her name&#8217;s Molly) and I use this time to really get my mind in the game so I&#8217;m quite prepared and less nervous when I arrive at the tournaments. Knowing your deck really well will almost always give you the winning edge in a close game. Knowing that you have passed 2 of your 3 trolls and 2 of your 3 Elendor&#8217;s Valour can make the difference between double moving for the win or staying put in indecision. My friend and play-tester extraordinaire, Jean-Luc Simard asked me if I wanted to car pool with him to the tournament but I declined knowing how important those 45 minutes of solo driving are to me and my state of mind. Between rounds, Josh from Toronto listens to Mozart, BadBeef has a smoke while his brother likes going to the bathroom, and me, I drive my car alone to concentrate. We all have our tricks and, for the most part, they make a difference. <br />
<br />
Holy cow, I&#8217;ve already written almost 1,000 words and I haven&#8217;t even talked about the actual tournament yet so I better get to it!<br />
<br />
So I arrive at the tournament right on time (after stopping at Tim Horton&#8217;s for coffee and muffin (the 2 dollar special is over! Darn!). I immediately check out the Singles Binders and manage to pick up a ROTEL Elrond and a Fear (cards for future decks). Great, now the only card I&#8217;m missing is Weapons of Isengard and my Wanted list will be barren! <br />
<br />
So 18 people have showed up so we&#8217;ll be playing 5 rounds. Pairings are called and we&#8217;re off:<br />
<br />
Round One (ding! ding!) <br />
Me (1941) vs. Jonathan Marian (1617) Choke/Dunland<br />
<br />
Jonathan is a fun opponent. Nice polite guy but darn. I don&#8217;t have any experience against Dunland decks. I&#8217;ll have to start playing it on my own son so I can understand the strategies a bit better. My friend, Patrick Malboeuf also has this problem. We both end up reading many of the cards as soon as they hit the table. Not good. It&#8217;s much better to know and be familiar with everything in play. David Malboeuf has the same problem against Raider decks. By not knowing the cards or implicit strategies therein, you tend to get overconfident, as you don&#8217;t assess the threats properly. Anyway, moot point. So I end up pulling Aragorn&#8217;s Bow and starting Greenleaeasterlingainst his Dunland. He gets a hides out early on but mistakenly discards it to prevent a wound. The next hides doesn&#8217;t show up until site 5 or 6 so I am gunning down the Dunland men like crazy. Meanwhile he&#8217;s choking me like crazy, double moving from 4-6 and giving me 4 twilight in the pool at site 6 with my holding on to 3 trolls in my hand. Anyway, I end up pulling it off regardless.<br />
FW +3/3<br />
Highs: Getting my archers set up early against Dunland<br />
	Playing Moria against a choke fellowship. That 4 twilight turned into almost a dozen minions.<br />
Lows: Me not knowing anything about Dunland and hence stopping at site 2 out of fear.<br />
<br />
Round Two<br />
Me (1941) vs. Christian Toupin (1595) Choke/Nazgul<br />
<br />
Christian is just as nice if not more than my previous opponent. Real fun guy. Always a smile on his face no matter what is happening in the game. Unfortunately his fellowship is a choke against my moria (unfair match-up for him) and his Nazgul are facing my choke fellowship with Filbert and O Elbereth (unfair Match-up for him). He could play as perfectly as possible and still not get even close to me. I think he also gave me only 4 twilight at site 6 after a double move. God bless those armories, relics, etc.<br />
FW +3/6<br />
Highs: Super opponent. <br />
	Me getting lucky with the pairings twice now.<br />
Lows: none. He&#8217;s too much fun to play against.<br />
<br />
Round three<br />
Me (1941) VS. Jean-Luc Simard (1699) Nazgul again!<br />
<br />
Jean-Luc has been getting closer and closer to beating me. Will he pull it off this time? Let&#8217;s watch...<br />
This was a game where we both played WAY too cowardly. We both had obvious double moves we should have made but elected to remain where we were. He was running over my moria like there was no tomorrow. Yet, he stayed at site 4. He again stayed at site 5. Meanwhile I stayed at site 6 when I had O Elbereth and Filbert on the table. In those circumstances, I think I should try to get to site 7 as fast as possible in order to double move 7-9 for the win. I still ended up doing it and winning at site 9 but I should have done it sooner. If he had double moved the two times he was supposed to, he would have won the game. His fellowship was way too tough for me.<br />
FW +3/9<br />
Highs: Pulling off a very lucky win.<br />
Lows:  Stressful game, stressful opponent. <br />
	Not having the balls to bypass the site 6 sanctuary<br />
<br />
Lunch time!<br />
I usually elect to go to the corner café that serves up a mean Eggs Benedict and killer Café au Lait, but two really nice players that I never get to play against invited me to go to Harvey&#8217;s (burger-joint) with them. So I break tradition for the first time and have a nice greasy lunch with some cool guys. Good choice, finally. Better than lunch by myself where I would have drank WAY too much coffee.<br />
<br />
Round Four<br />
Me (1941) vs. Alan Marchand (1603) Nazgul AGAIN.<br />
<br />
Alan is one of my favourite opponents. We&#8217;ve only played twice but he is CRAZY nice and looks just like a Dwarf (beard, stocky, etc.).  He was wearing this really cool green shirt that I had told him earlier on would bring him great luck today. Turns out, he was the unluckiest of all my opponents. So I end up winning the bid and start Riddermark with Eowyn and Greenleaf. He starts Aragorn! I couldn&#8217;t understand it. I asked him about it after the game and he said he didn&#8217;t know you were allowed to pick starting companions AFTER the site is revealed. He thought it was fixed from the beginning. Turns out, he only had one other unbound companion, Boromir, so even if he Wanted to start someone else, he wouldn&#8217;t be able to go fetch Aragorn. I suggested he throw in Merry, Friend to Sam, so that next time, he could take advantage of the Riddermark&#8217;s game text. So Alan plays pretty quickly and I got out an Armory and Relic of Moria into my support area with all 4 scimitars in my discard pile by site 3! So his move to site 4 was certainly as rough as it gets. Frodo perished and then some. It took less than 5 minutes and our game was over. I was amazed. His shadow certainly worked well, though. Out comes Toldea at site 2, which stopped me. However, he then doubled to 3 with just Aragorn and Frodo. Leaving him pretty naked going to site 4.<br />
FW +3/12<br />
Highs: Alan for being a fun opponent and resembling a dwarf and being proud about that.<br />
	2 companions as starting fellowship against moria. Yay!<br />
	None of the Nazgul players so far are playing All Blades Perish. <br />
Lows:	Our game was too short. I would have liked to have a full game with him... <br />
<br />
<br />
Round Five<br />
Me (1941) vs. Alexandre Leblanc (1740) Hobbits / Uruk Site control<br />
<br />
Alex is one of those stressed-out players. I guess I should consider myself lucky that I got to play 3 really calm players today which makes for a much more fun and relaxing game. Even day two DecipherCon, I had almost ALL calm players (Mike Dalton, Andy McClure (dude!), John Irving (Dude!) and many others where I can only remember their faces). So why does a LOCAL tournament have so many crazy-stressed players when the world championships didn&#8217;t? Anyway, the name of this particular match was running like crazy. We both double moved every chance we got. He didn&#8217;t control one site until very late in the game. At that point, I had made it past a Vanguard (Yay Swiftly & Softly) so my confidence was way up. It was a very close game. Good thing he didn&#8217;t get his site control going until late in the game otherwise his Burning of Westfold would have killed my choking capability. <br />
FW +3 / 15<br />
Highs: My confidence all game was very high, (which really helps)<br />
	Swiftly and softly on a power 19 damage +2 vanguard<br />
Lows:	Stressed out opponent equals stressful game...<br />
<br />
So I win the tourney going undefeated once again. Moria&#8217;s still got it! So does choke! It was a real fun tournament and I can&#8217;t wait to go back!<br />
<br />
Props: Alan Marchand, Christian Toupin and Jonathan Marian for being such calm and fun opponents. Always smiling and joking... they greatly contribute to a healthy gaming environment.<br />
<br />
Slops: Not getting to play Alain or Carle Bérard (they would have been really fun games too).<br />
<br />
Major Slops: N.A.S.A. for not upgrading their out-dated shuttle technology. I think the top brass over there should be forced to drive Pintos for a few months... <br></font></blockquote><BR><font class="bfont"> <A HREF='/lotr/treports/treports.php?id=4195&view=1'>Read the Reviews</a><font class="bfont"> | <A HREF='/lotr/treports/treports.php'>Back to List</A></font><p><font class="bfont"> <b>You must be a member to contribute to Decktech.</b>  <p>Please <a href='/lotr/main/join.php'> become a registered member</a></font></font></td><td background="/lotr/gfx/mom/whi_09.gif"></td></tr>
